default&#xa0;defaultWritten evidence fromdefault the Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the Medical Research Councildefault (MRC)default default[defaultOD0default16default]default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;
defaultPublicly funded and collected 
defaultdata 
defaultcan have a significant value for economic growth, for health and for society more broadly. The Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the 
defaultMedical Research Council (MRC) are committed to 
defaultthe RCUK Common Principles on Data Policy
default, which set out an overarching framework for individual research councils’ data policies
default 
default. The RCUK principles 
defaultrecognise that publicly funded research data are a public good, produced in the public interest and should be made openly available with a
defaults
default few restrictions as possible in a timely and responsible manner.  Research data generated by research council funding must be discoverable, accessible and usable. In addition to funding research programmes which generate data
default,
default the research councils also support infrastructure, build capacity in key disciplines and deliver a policy framework for data sharing and preservation which ensure the research community and others can maximise the value of data.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultWhy is open data important?default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default8.
default              
defaultAs noted in the introduction above, the research councils are committed to the principle that publicly-funded data should be openly available to the maximum extent possible, this may include open-data publication or some form of managed access to ensure data are safe. 
default 
default It is also important to ensure
default that 
defaultdata made open
default 
defaultare
default used and re-used by suitably qualified, trained and experienced researchers as effectively as possible
default; this is
default in order to 
defaultmaintain the integrity of the data and to ensure the trust of research participants, both of which are essential to 
defaultmaximise its contribution to informing public policy and services
default. This is particularly important when bringing together data produced by different government departments or public bodies where individual’s identities may inadvertently be discoverable; thus suitable governance arrangements may need to considered to undertake cross-departmental analyses.
